          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
       Ukraine‚Äôs drone warfare
       </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
         <strong>
         Summary: Operation Spider‚Äôs Web showcased Ukraine‚Äôs innovative use of drones to strike deep into Russian territory.</strong>
         </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
            Operation Spider‚Äôs Web <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-5-jun-25-analysis-h1-9-marked-a-key-change" target="_blank">marked a key change</a> in modern warfare. On Sunday, Ukrainian forces hit four major Russian air bases, including Olenya, Diaghilevo, Belaya, and Ivanovo. They damaged over 40 strategic aircraft, including Tu-95MS, Tu-22M3, Tu-160 bombers, and rare A-50 AWACS planes. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        The operation used small drones launched discreetly from cargo trucks smuggled into Russia. These drones were controlled via LTE networks and stabilized by ArduPilot software. They likely had AI-assisted targeting focused on the aircraft's weak points. The attacks showed flaws in Russia's rear defenses and weakened its long-range missile strikes. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        By targeting training and repair hubs, Ukraine disrupted Russia's strategic aviation support. This mission highlighted the power of open-source autonomy, operational deception, and precise targeting. Spider‚Äôs Web illustrates how agility, innovation, and asymmetry are transforming the battlefield, not just at the front lines.
          </p>
         
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
