          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
   How does Hajj influence geopolitics?
</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/hajj-pilgrimage-heat-stress-deaths-health-risks.jpg" alt="With nearly 2Mn people participating each year, it is not unusual for pilgrims to die from heat stress, illness, or chronic disease during the hajj" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
          <i>With nearly 2Mn people participating each year, it is not unusual for pilgrims to die from heat stress, illness, or chronic disease during the hajj. Credits: Agence France-Presse</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">     
        Hajj is an <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-5-jun-25-foundations-h1-16-annual-pilgrimage" target="_blank">annual pilgrimage</a> to Mecca that every adult Muslim must undertake at least once if they are able. However, there are some geopolitical aspects in the background. As the host of the pilgrims, Saudi Arabia holds significant soft power in the Muslim world. Its rule over Mecca and Medina enhances its religious authority and influence in global Islamic affairs.  
        </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Saudi Arabia utilizes this status to enhance its regional leadership. It often uses it to <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-5-jun-25-foundations-h1-17-manage-sectarian-issues" target="_blank">manage sectarian issues</a>, especially between Sunni Saudi Arabia and Shia-majority Iran. Entry to the Mecca can also become a diplomatic issue. Saudi Arabia sets quotas for each country, limiting the number of pilgrims who can attend each year. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">     
        These quotas can cause disputes in strained political relationships, such as those with Iran or Qatar. Many find these quotas unfair. While Israelis are banned from Saudi Arabia, including the 2Mn Arab Muslims who are citizens, Israeli Muslims may get a <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-5-jun-25-foundations-h1-18-temporary-jordanian-passport" target="_blank">temporary Jordanian passport</a> to enter the country for Hajj / Umrah purposes.
        </p>
        <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">     
        The Kingdom‚Äôs ability to efficiently and safely host pilgrims bolsters its leadership image across the Muslim world. In times of crisis, such as pandemics or conflicts, decisions around Hajj restrictions carry significant political weight. 
        </p>
        </mj-text>
